In article <CwJBtH.5G@chinet.chinet.com>, schneier@chinet.chinet.com (Bruce Schneier) writes:

|>In article <strnlghtCwCLoD.CEL@netcom.com>,
|>David Sternlight <strnlght@netcom.com> wrote:
|>>In article <CwA0K7.KMF@chinet.chinet.com>,
|>>Bruce Schneier <schneier@chinet.chinet.com> wrote:
|>>>
|>>>The main question seems to be whether or not the State Department would
|>>>pull fast export approval for RC4 with key lengths of 40 bits orless. 
|>>
|>>Now, Bruce, surely I shouldn't have to remind you that if RC4 is published,
|>>then the export licenses for shorter key versions lose their protection of
|>>U.S. security interests since on the other end a recipient may drop in a
|>>longer-key version of RC4 while maintaining compatibility.
|>
|>Interesting theory, but it seems not to be true.  In fact, what is coming
|>out is the the government never gave a tinker's damn whether or not RC4
|>was public or not.  RSADSI wanted the algorithm secret.
|>
|>If "at the other end a recipient may drop in a longer-key version of RC4,"
|>the same recipient can just as easily drop in DES, triple-DES, IDEA, of
|>whatever else he wanted to.

Only reason I can see for keeping RC4 secret would be for RSA's benefit. 
There are many symetric key block ciphers avaliable. One more is not
going to cause anyone to have sleepless nights.

So anyone want to write up an informational RFC on the cipher and submit it to
the IETF? I would like an extra cipher to add into HTTP.

